observations.recommendation:
We recommended the Management to direct all concerned officials on the effective, active and full implementation of the following:
close monitoring and implementation of significant SWM PPAs as planned and budgeted to maximize the benefits that could be derived therefrom;
willful enforcement of existing ordinances and their fines and penalties to effectively and efficiently implement SWM, especially on the segregation, collecting, and disposal of solid wastes;
the provision of incentives to performing barangays/communities primarily to encourage active participation in the implementation of the SWM Plan; and
employment of appropriate action to address the delayed expansion of the garbage collection coverage of the LGU to catch up with the target number of barangays per year in accordance with the SWM Plan.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
a) 	Municipal Accountant to provide and maintain the necessary Subsidiary Ledgers of RPT and SET Receivables by initially adopting the Real Property Tax Account Registers or Taxpayer’s Index Cards being maintained by the Office of the Municipal Treasurer;
b) 	Municipal Assessor, the Municipal Treasurer, and the Municipal Accountant to jointly identify, investigate, trace, and correct prior years’ errors and/or misstatements in RPT and SET Receivables in order to close the gap between these two related accounts and reflect more reliable balances in the next accounting period/s;
c) 	Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries to correct the discrepancy in the year end balances of the RPT and SET Receivables once established; and
d) 	Municipal Treasurer to ensure that equal amount shall be collected and reported for both the basic and special education taxes for every payment of the taxpayers.

We recommended that Management:
Execute contracts of lease with all operators of fish cages/pens and tenants of market facilities;
Strictly enforce the remedies indicated in the lease contract upon default by the lessor;
Maintain an updated list of fish cages/pens operators and market stalls tenants to ensure that the awarded operators and tenants are the rightful occupants;
Maximize the utilization of the Offices of the Market Supervisor and the Lake Development Office in ensuring the enforcement of the terms and conditions of the contract;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to review all the lease contracts entered into by the LGU and its lessees especially the terms of payment in order to ensure that the billings and collections are based on the agreed terms and conditions, and furnish the Audit Team with copies of the duly authenticated Lease Contracts and other supporting documents, if necessary; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to set-up a Trust Liability account for the rental deposits, if there is any.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:

the Municipal Treasurer to strictly implement the daily preparation of RCD by each Collecting Officer in order to assure the regular remittance of all collections for the day to the Municipal Treasurer;

the Municipal Treasurer to monitor the issued Accountable Forms (AF) to the Collecting Officers so as to ensure remittance of all previously issued AF prior the release of  another stub;

the Municipal Accountant to prepare JEV for all the LGU transactions and attach the same to the accounts being submitted to the Audit Team; and

the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries to record the collections in CY 2020.

We recommended that Management direct the:

Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to account for the ₱1.85 unconfirmed LBP balances as of December 31, 2020;
Municipal Treasurer to immediately submit to the Office of the Municipal Accountant the Disbursement Vouchers and its supporting documents totaling ₱282,564.00/ to take up the unrecorded disbursements or proof that errors were indeed committed by the bank to adjust the alleged bank errors;
Municipal Accountant to prepare and record the adjusting journal entry in the  agency books to revert back to the appropriate funds the stale checks totaling ₱1.59 million and establish the liability of the Municipality;
Municipal Accountant to record the journal entries to take up the Debit and Credit Memos, deposit in transit, and unrecorded deposits; and
Municipal Accountant to exert more effort by assigning one personnel to reevaluate the previous BRSs, to track down the unreconciled items totaling ₱1.64 million and ₱1.80 million which are additions to and deductions from bank balances as of December 31, 2020, respectively.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:

Municipal Accountant to provide and maintain the necessary Subsidiary Ledgers of RPT and SET Receivables by initially adopting the Real Property Tax Account Registers or Taxpayer’s Index Cards being maintained by the Office of the Municipal Treasurer;
Municipal Accountant to comply with the recommended accounting entries in recording collections of RPT and SET Receivables;
Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries to correct the discrepancy in the year end balances of the RPT/SET Receivables and Deferred RPT/SET; and
Municipal Treasurer to ensure that equal amount be collected for both the basic and special education taxes for every payment of the taxpayers.

We recommended that Management:

send letters to the concerned officers and employees demanding the immediate settlement/liquidation of their outstanding cash advances through the submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports and enforce the withholding of salary, in accordance with Section 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 if no action is taken after the lapse of the timeline set in the demand letter;
stop the granting of additional cash advance for travel and training to personnel with unliquidated cash advances unless the previous cash advance/s is/are fully settled;
require the Municipal Accountant to provide subsidiary ledger where the details of the cash advances and liquidations of each Accountable Officer shall be recorded; and
monitor and establish controls to ensure the timely liquidation of cash advances through updated monthly aging of the same to prevent accumulation of unliquidated cash advances.

We recommended that Management and the Municipal Treasurer to:

update the database wherein complete information of the capitalization, annual gross receipts, and other relevant data of business establishments of the Municipality is stored;
endeavor to come up with complete database of business establishments thru regular tax mapping and coordination with barangays which have records/information of existing businesses within their jurisdictions;
generate complete List of Delinquent Business Establishment Taxpayers to facilitate the demand and collection of the business taxes in arrears;
improve the computerized Masterlist of Business Establishments in order that generated reports and information furnished to users and decision makers be reflective of the exact raw data from the automated system; and
continue efforts and activities that contribute to the realization and attainment of the target collections while undertaking necessary measures to maximize revenue from business taxes.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
cause for the immediate submission of the seven DVs totaling ₱2,183,292.86 to the Office of the OIC-Municipal Accountant for recording and eventually to the Commission on Audit, otherwise, the entire unrecorded check disbursements shall be suspended in audit;
require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to submit the BRS as of December 31, 2019 of the remaining Municipal bank accounts;
initiate the necessary administrative action to enforce the timely submission of the Report of Checks Issued and the entire accounts from the Office of the Municipal Treasurer to the Office of Municipal Accountant and eventually to the Audit Team in compliance with Section 44 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Acting Municipal Accountant to:
Submit to the Auditor the supporting documents of all accumulated accounts payable as reflected in the Schedule of AP as of December 31, 2019 to back up the authenticity of the recorded obligations in the books of accounts of the Municipal Government;
Identify the veracity, nature and claim of the recorded payables both for the current and prior years’ ledgers/files to determine which are valid claims;
Take up the appropriate reversion/adjustments in the books of the LGU for those established transactions with no valid claimants and with dormant accounts in order to have a fair presentation of accounts in the financial statements; and
Maintain SL for all accounts showing the details of information.

We recommended that Management require the:
1.) Municipal Budget Officer to project a realizable revenue from its Economic Enterprises (i.e. Market, Slaughterhouse and Cemetery);
2.)  Economic Enterprises’ administrators to implement strategies that will boost the revenue from its operation;
3.) Municipal Accountant to reflect the amount of Personal Services for each of the Economic Enterprises in its separate financial statements in order to reflect the actual performance and a proper evaluation of the operations can be made.

We recommended that the Management:
coordinate and follow up with the Provincial Government of Camarines Sur as to the status of enforcement of the General Revision, in order to avoid the lax imposition of the supposedly increase in tax collections; and
direct the Municipal Assessor to make sure that the fair market values of the real properties, including the improvements, are properly reflected in the tax declarations and FAASs;
